Hadn't seen anything saying that mass ratios or delta-V is higher than an old fission Orion. Given the technology to make these, fission bomb Orion is also improved, so it's a toss-up.<br>
 The question is fuel. With large scale activity in space, fission power plants might be as useful as a wind-driven generator on an airplane -sure it works, but why? Solar is everywhere and the main feedstock is metal-film mirror instead of highly refined U ores.<br>
OTOH, it is simple and useful as a power source, and even ground-based power plants could provide a cheap fuel source for Orion (Breeder cycle).<br>
<br>
For micro-fusion, it's a technical challenge to ignite the pellets and again, improvements here only help Orion, too. With easy solutions to the problems with ICAN/ACMF, Daedalus, or mini-orion, old fashioned fission bombs are also cheaper &amp; simpler.<br>
<br>
If we get out to a source of He3 (better than the Moon), then it's a lot better. Maybe even clean enough for a fusion-pulse powered atmospheric booster...<br>
I'd also like to learn more about the 11Boron7 + proton reaction. A certain amount of protons being bombarded onto a certain molecule of an isotope of Boron and the reaction gives off extremely energetic He atoms minus the electrons, easily directed by fields -and no ionizing radiation whatsoever.<br>
<br>
However, I don't see this ever being used as an Earth-to-LEO lifting system. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=megaloman84>Megaloman84</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/18/03 10:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=145>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Orion</span><hr size=1> While I think ongoing discussion of Orion is probably a good thing, if only as a baseline against which to judge alternatives. More research on my part has not reversed my previous opinion that there are numerous propulsion solution that simply make more sense than NPR.<br>
<br>
Orion has some serious problems.  For example, the Orion pusher plate was designed so that its thickness at any given point matched the momentum of the plasma stream that would impact it.  This was done so that the entire plate would experience uniform acceleration and not be ripped apart by the difference in exerted force from the center to the perimeter of the pusher.  While this would probably work well enough most of the time, even a small mis-alignment of the PU would result in the catastrophic destruction of the pusher.<br>
<br>
Also, I am generally less than impressed with the engine-out abort capability of Orion, especially within the atmosphere.<br>
<br>
Considering that GCNRs often exceed the ISP of Orion-type spacecraft, and can be done with even less new technology and engineering, I see no reason to push for the implementation of Orions.  If we really want large, heavy spacecraft with copious amount of disposable delta V, they could be done just as well with any number of propulsion schemes.<br>
<br>
Of course, they couldn't  be earth launched, but good luck getting Clarence for a ground-launched Orion anyway.<br>
<br>
Another advantage of most non-Orion propulsion mechanisms is they scale down nicely. <br>
<br>
An NTR or NEP drive could be used to launch a small, Mars-direct style manned craft within half a dozen years.<br>
<br>
For most near-term applications, an Orion sized craft would simply be overkill.  Despite higher unit costs, the total cost of an aggressive space program utilizing more modest craft powered by existing(I mean existing in the broad sense that operational prototypes have existed in the past, if not now) technologies could probably be done much cheaper. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=orion@nuclearspace>Orion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/19/03 5:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=146>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Short term.</span><hr size=1> The way i see it nuclear pulse propulsion is decades away. There are other that should be developed first. Like something akin to the Liberty ship and alike. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=q66stang>Q66stang</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 37<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/19/03 9:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=147>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Short term.</span><hr size=1> Theredcomin<br>
