Hadn't seen anything saying that mass ratios or delta-V is higher than an old fission Orion.<br>
------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
I believe it must be so, because the efficiency of the fusion reaction is so much better  -- about 10 times better in terms of mass--energy conversion, as I recall. If so, this can be translated into a better mass ratio (ie., higher payload fraction) or higher delta-V for the same payload fraction. <br>
<br>
------------------------------------<br>
The question is fuel. With large scale activity in space, fission power plants might be as useful as a wind-driven generator on an airplane -sure it works, but why? Solar is everywhere and the main feedstock is metal-film mirror instead of highly refined U ores.<br>
------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
Well, two points here.<br>
<br>
(1) Leaving aside the H3 debate (a separate issue) micro-fusion by power laser on pellet does not require expensive and rare fuel like U235 or Pl. Hydrogen is plentiful like nothing else is in the universe.<br>
<br>
(2) Solar is everywhere, but there's less and less of it the further you get from the Sun; by the time you get to Mars orbit, it's at about 1/3rd the intensity around the earth, and by Saturn it's almost neglegable. IOW, it ain't going to do the job.<br>
<br>
------------------------------------<br>
For micro-fusion, it's a technical challenge...<br>
------------------------------------<br>
<br>
<br>
